Today is the day we honor the mom's in our lives and the contribution women make. 

Today I think about my grandmother, the first to come to faith in our family. I'm thankful that she preached the gospel to my grandfather, an unlikely candidate to become the patriarch of a Godly heritage. It all started with her. 

Today I think about my mother, who was a rock of faith in our home until her home going at 54 years old. She preached the good news to me and my siblings in so many ways. She still does. 

Today I think about my wife Debbie, who is the quiet, steady guiding force of faith in our family. She has preached the gospel with her life and is a living example of an "excellent wife". I am so grateful for her. 

Today I think about my daughters and daughter in laws, who navigate a different world than I knew, as they preach the gospel to their children, to an amazing church and to a culture that often attempts to shape their families in ways contrary to their faith. They are champions in my eyes. 

Today I think about my 10 granddaughters, who are already preaching the gospel in their world, sometimes in spite of those who tell them that they can't. Look out world, there is a new generation being unleashed, who will do great works in their time. I can't wait to see it come to pass. 

Today I think of the great women of the Bible, both Old and New Testaments, who preached the gospel in sometimes difficult times. Deborah, Ruth, Mary, Mary, Junia, Phoebe, Priscilla and others who stood up when others perhaps shied away. You led the way and I'm blessed because of you. 

Today I think of many of you, like my daughter in law Lisa, who will preach the gospel faithfully in congregations on this day that honors you. May you speak with boldness and clarity, with insight and humor, with truth and love. May God's blessing rest upon your words and God's peace settle your spirits. 

Today we honor you. 

God's got your back.

I’ve been using an app called “readwise“ for the last couple of months, and I love it. It helps me to remember what it was that I liked about the books that I’ve read. My process:

1. I read a book in kindle and highlight the parts I want to remember.

2. The highlights are automatically transferred to readwise.

3. Every morning I review five or six highlights from the books I’ve read (automatically curated through readwise). 

4. If I so desire, the app will make a photo of any of the highlights from that day, like the one that I’m posting today from NT Wright (which I read several months ago). 

For me, this has been a game changer in helping me remember what I’ve learned, and what I liked about the books I’ve read. 

I know I’m probably late to the game, but is there anyone else that uses this app? If so, do you have a similar process? 

#readwise

WHAT I LOVE ABOUT MY CHURCH. 

Actually, it’s just ONE of the things:

The 1st pic shows the weather at church time. It’s pretty awesome if you are a duck 🦆. 

The second one shows my view from the front row. THERE’S A CLUE HERE IN WHAT I LOVE ABOUT MY CHURCH. 

I awoke this morning to tropical storm like weather on a Sunday. My first thoughts were gratitude for online church, we have no responsibilities today, put a fire in the fireplace, coffee in the cup and worship from the couch. To stay home would have been a reasonable choice, and this post is not covertly aimed at those who did. That’s not the point. 

Due to travel I hadn’t been to Seacoast in a month, I decided to get the rain gear out and wade through the water. Let’s do this together. 

THE SECOND PIC TELLS THE STORY. 

The building is less than half full and yet the front rows are packed. By choice, not assignment. In anticipation. 

That’s it. 

It’s not about the number of people in the house, it’s about the anticipation of those who are there.

Here’s what I have noticed in my travels: Even in a full house, often times the last to fill are the front rows. It’s not that way in a concert, or sporting event, but it’s often the case in a church. How many times have you experienced a late coming guest being reluctantly ushered to the front few rows? 

Why?

I don’t know. What I do know is that when the front fills first, there is a sense of anticipation that filters up to the platform and infects even those leading the services. 

HERE’S MY CHALLENGE TO YOU: You can increase the anticipation quotient in your local church by something as simple as moving to the front few rows. And inviting friends to join you. 

Adam Martin, our teacher this morning challenged us at the end of his great message on joy: “If you want to learn to swim, you’ve got get closer to the water. If you want to get warm, you’ve got to get closer to the fire. If you want to have joy, you’ve got to get closer to the author and giver of joy.”

Would it be a leap too far to include: “And the closer you are to the front, the better the experience is for everyone”?

Maybe so, but is something I love about our church.

#seacoastchurch
